cophiliacs, whose subjectivity was grounded in a social rather than an individualistic context. By attending concerts, learning instruments, and performing at home and in various urban environments, musicophiliacs embodied forms of modernity that were distinct from those found in the West. In tracing the relationship between musical practices and the formation of the social subject, Niranjana opens up new ways to think about urbanity, subjectivity, culture, and multiple modernities.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 03. Jan 2023) 0aHindustani musicxSocial aspectszIndiazMumbai. 0aHindustani musiczIndiazMumbaixHistory and criticism. 7aHISTORY / Asia / India & South Asia.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDuke University Press Complete eBook-Package 2020z97831106963180 cprintz978147800686240uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781478009191?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781478009191423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781478009191/original  a978-3-11-069631-8  Duke University Press Complete eBook-Package 2020b2020  aEBA_DUK_ALL  aEBA_DUK_EALL  aEBA_DUK_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles